                "name": "Viktor T. Toth",
                "href": "/profile/Viktor-T-Toth-1"
            },
            "answer_text": "It depends on where the listener is located. Space does not carry sound. So when you are some distance away from a star or black hole, you hear nothing. But descend into a stellar atmosphere and you\u2019ll be subjected to the loudest noises possible (of course you\u2019ll also be fried in no time, but let\u2019s ignore that.) The gas swirls about at speeds exceeding that of terrestrial hurricanes by orders of magnitude. It is an incredibly noisy place. As for black holes, the object itself is just a distortion of spacetime geometry, but the infalling matter is another thing altogether. The accretion disk that it forms may get dense enough in places to carry sound in a meaningful sense; and again, the \u201cwinds\u201d are so incredibly powerful, and thus incredibly loud. ",
